We’re introducing Scene Keypoint Consistency into the keypoint scoring mechanism. 

We now track how stable keypoints remain inside continuous frame sequences.

For each frame, we match the same keypoint indices from the previous frame, calculate the average movement in pixels, and normalise it by the image diagonal for resolution independence.

This stability score is now a scaling factor in the final evaluation, meaning unstable sequences will reduce your overall score.

# Score Vision — Roadmap

## Where we are (Perceive ✅ live)

•⁠  ⁠*What’s live:* Frame-level understanding for football (soccer): ball, players, pitch keypoints + homography → reliable XY coordinates per frame.
•⁠  ⁠*Value today:* Reconstruct game state and derive team shapes, pressure/space maps, offside lines, tempo and phase,purely from Perceive outputs.
•⁠  ⁠*Data stream:* We’re aggregating labeled, structured football data (XY + metadata) and preparing listings on several data marketplaces for bettors, media, and research buyers.
•⁠  ⁠*Access:* *Score Vision as a Service* (white-glove) is running with PoCs - partners submit video, receive labeled data back. A broader self-serve front end is planned.

## What’s next (order may change)

•⁠  ⁠*Larger clips & streaming ingestion* for smoother context across possessions and live games.
•⁠  ⁠*Hardened validation*: a VLM-based judge - scales vertically (harder tests) and horizontally (new sports/verticals).
•⁠  ⁠*Understand (PoCs with data consumers):* event spotting beyond per-frame entities—goals, fouls, ball out/in, kick-off, free kicks, restarts. Unlocks significant downstream revenue.
•⁠  ⁠*Predict (prototype challenges):* miners train deep nets to forecast event windows (likelihood and timing), leveraging Perceive + Understand signals.
•⁠  ⁠*Cross-sport expansion:* we’ll introduce new sports and other video verticals, always starting with Perceive, then layering Understand → Predict.
•⁠  ⁠*SVaaS evolution:* move from white-glove to a *self-serve portal + APIs* (submit video → get structured data), with usage-based billing.

## The three phases (our simple mental model)

### 1) Perceive — “What’s on the screen?”

•⁠  ⁠Entities and geometry per frame (live for football).
•⁠  ⁠Foundation for everything else: repeatable XY → consistent downstream features.

### 2) Understand — “What’s happening?”

•⁠  ⁠Context and events over time (spotting goals, fouls, restarts, etc.).
•⁠  ⁠Target outcome: production-ready event streams validated by robust scoring; PoCs with large data buyers.

### 3) Predict — “What happens next?”

•⁠  ⁠Learned probabilities for events and tactical moments.
•⁠  ⁠Uses: broadcast alerts, scouting, coaching support, integrity, and markets.

## For miners & validators

•⁠  ⁠Expect *longer clips, streaming tasks, and more varied footage types*.
•⁠  ⁠Scoring will move to a *VLM judge* approach with much higher accuracy.
•⁠  ⁠Rewards will continue to emphasise *accuracy and speed* across different contexts.

## Principles

•⁠  ⁠*No artificial deadlines.* We ship continuously as components harden.
•⁠  ⁠*Generalise by design.* Built to port across sports and non-sports video.
•⁠  ⁠*Pragmatic access.* White-glove now; self-serve when it’s robust.

It’s about what happens after the data is collected here at @score・44.

### From Coordinates to Context

With XY coordinates, analysts generate tracking or “360 data” by stitching together player and ball positions across all frames of a match. Ball tracking enhances this further by recognizing possession events such as passes, carries, and shots. This approach transforms football analysis from a player-centric view to a holistic system of interactions on the pitch.

As outlined by StatsBomb comparison between event data and tracking data, event data provides only snapshots of the player with the ball. In contrast, tracking data contextualizes each event by showing the positioning and movement of all players. This richer framework allows analysts to evaluate not only what happened, but also what could have happened.

### Enhanced Metrics and Deeper Insights

Tracking data enables new performance metrics and improvements to existing models. For instance, Hudl’s xPass 360 (https://www.hudl.com/blog/xpass-360-upgrading-expected-pass-xpass-models) upgrade illustrates how expected pass models become more accurate when incorporating the positioning of teammates, opponents, and space. 

Similarly, StatsBomb’s new 360 metrics allow analysts to quantify line-breaking passes (https://blogarchive.statsbomb.com/articles/soccer/statsbomb-launch-new-360-metrics-line-breaking-passes-and-ball-receipts-in-space-2/) and evaluate ball receipts in space, key elements of effective attacking play.

This shift means that actions are judged not just by their outcome, but by their difficulty and context. A forward pass through a tight defensive line, for example, can be weighted differently than a simple lateral pass, offering more meaningful evaluations of player decision-making and execution.

### Beyond Events: Use Cases of Tracking Data

Tracking data also powers advanced use cases beyond possession events:

- Pitch Control Models (https://www.sfu.ca/~tswartz/papers/pitch_control.pdf): Using methods outlined in Swartz’s pitch control paper, analysts can measure which areas of the field each team controls at any moment. This has applications in evaluating formations, identifying spaces left open, and quantifying pressing intensity (Merckx et al. 2021, Unravel Sports 2024).

- Formations and Team Shape: As shown in EightyFivePoints (https://www.google.com/url?q=https://eightyfivepoints.blogspot.com/2019/11/using-data-to-analyse-team-formations.html&sa=D&source=docs&ust=1755704252019460&usg=AOvVaw2PQ9_GlFf63eSOlSM6lVb_) analysis, tracking data helps analysts objectively identify formations, compactness, and tactical adjustments across phases of play.

- Game-Changing Applications (https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/5-game-changing-use-cases-football-tracking-data-why-matter-v2eqe/): From pressing analysis to player development, tracking data has been identified as transformative for football clubs and federations

- Pressing Intensity (https://unravelsports.github.io/2024/12/12/pressing-intensity.html): UnravelSports introduced an intuitive metric called Pressing Intensity, which quantifies defensive pressure at the individual frame level. It uses positional tracking data along with a time-to-intercept model—from Spearman’s Pitch Control framework, to calculate how much pressure each defender applies to each attacker dynamically and accurately

- Defensive Analysis: A Deeper Tactical View

Tracking data has profoundly enhanced the analysis of defensive play, an area traditionally harder to quantify than attacking actions. A 2022 scoping review of tracking-based defensive studies revealed that effective defense isn't just about tackles or clearances, but also about spatial and tactical coordination. At the individual level, strong defensive pressure around the ball correlates with success. At the group level, successful defenses exhibit high synchronization both within the team and between the team and opponents, maintaining balanced coverage. And at the team level, compact and coordinated defensive organization is a key indicator of defensive performance  Groningen Research Portal (https://pure.rug.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/258896058/17479541221075734.pdf)

Tracking data thus empowers analysts to evaluate defensive behavior in contextual, dynamic, and multidimensional terms, far beyond what traditional event data could offer.

They’ve agreed to work with Score to receive signals from our full tech stack (both on and off subnet), with subnet 44 contributing specific features extracted from annotated footage. Where confusion often arises is around the term “AUM.”

In traditional finance, AUM means the total market value of assets under management, stocks, bonds, funds, real estate, tied to fees and long-term fiduciary duty. In betting, AUM is used far more loosely. It usually refers to the bankroll or credit line deployed daily across markets. LPs guarantee coverage up to a fixed figure, and the line is rolled over as bets settle.

So while both involve managing capital for returns, the dynamics are different. Betting AUM is closer to a daily operating bankroll than a long-term pool of assets. When performance is strong, the bankroll rolls forward; when it dips, liquidity calls are made, similar to margin calls in finance. Put simply: AUM in betting is the amount LPs are willing to risk over a season, not an asset base under long-term management.
